But even as the country works to mitigate the effects of the virus, we should not ignore the learning side of the pandemic as a “systems flaw detector” and work harder and smarter to address the weaknesses that it exposes in the various sectors so as to build on both stopgap and lasting steadiness and resilience. 

Under the Covid-19 spell, the most severely strained sector in the country has been the national healthcare delivery one, whose capacity and efficiency is still wanting even as the third wave of the virus, which appears to be far more overwhelming than the earlier ones, starts. 

Already, there are calls for speedy modification and system improvement to healthcare to avoid a looming disaster following the fresh increase in the national tally of infections and deaths. 

Tested to the limit 

The virus has also tested our socioeconomic environment to the limit, judging by the limping economy with poor circulation of money as well as slow resumption to learning, foreign travel and tourism, which could degenerate once again due to the new wave. 



